{
  "text": "In addition to informing fisheries management decisions, baseline information on biodiversity and species interactions in the region is increasingly important at a time when South Georgia is facing rapid ocean warming [CITATION_1] and new marine protected areas are being introduced to protect the ecosystem [CITATION_2] . In January 2003 a deepwater bottom trawl survey was undertaken to investigate the biota found on areas of the shelf and continental slope at depths down to 1000 m. This is the only deepwater demersal trawl survey that has been successfully carried out to date at South Georgia, and this paper reviews the data collected during that survey and examines the distribution and community structure of demersal fish species in the region.",
